To create a TikZ diagram that represents the relative error percentage and relative speedup percentage of DFT and RA methods for various ciphertext lengths, you can use the following LaTeX code:

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=5mm]{standalone}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.18}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
    \begin{axis}[
        title={Relative Error Percentage and Speedup},
        xlabel={Ciphertext Length},
        ylabel={Percentage},
        ymin=-20,
        ymax=20,
        ybar interval=20pt,
        bar width=30pt,
        symbolic x coords={16, 32, 64, 128, 256},
        xtick=data,
        nodes near coords,
        nodes near coords align={vertical},
        ]

        % Relative Error Percentage Data
        \addplot[fill=blue!70] coordinates {(16,-10) (32,-5) (64,0) (128,5) (256,10)};
        \legend{Relative Error Percentage}

        % Relative Speedup Percentage Data
        \addplot[fill=red!70] coordinates {(16,20) (32,15) (64,10) (128,5) (256,0)};
        \legend{Relative Speedup Percentage}

    \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code creates a bar chart with two bars representing the relative error percentage and relative speedup percentage for different ciphertext lengths (16, 32, 64, 128, and 256). The `ymin` and `ymax` values set the range of the y-axis to ensure both data sets are visible.

The `\addplot` commands add the data points for each metric, with blue bars for relative error and red bars for relative speedup. The `nodes near coords` option displays the exact values next to each bar for clarity.

You can compile this code using a LaTeX editor that supports TikZ and pgfplots, such as Overleaf or TeXShop. Adjust the data points as needed to match your specific results.

